* Ariel: duckdb can be considered an experiment (continued from bigquery, by some of
  the original authors) to bring sanity to SQL by focusing on a subset or
  extending what is needed and doing it to work against CSV or Parquet files
  without needing a real database engine
* about apache datafusion: DataFusion is an extensible query engine written in
  Rust that uses Apache Arrow as its in-memory format.
  Apache Arrow as in-memory format and Apache Parquet as the format for both file
  and network transmission. Duckdb can use both, so can do the latest versions of
  Panda and any really good lib.
  https://datafusion.apache.org/user-guide/sql/struct_coercion.html#null-handling-for-missing-fields
  they override standard SQL with implicit CAST/COERCE where needed so behavior
  is sane.
* Datafusion/Duckdb can also work directly against sqlite, which is more "on
  topic" respect to Arcan. They shine with S3 parqued parquet files and
  interacting with other legacy databases like postgres, today's JDBC.
